Big deal about to close... but it‚Äôs not the ICP?

When I work on refining sales strategies for scale ups, I always include a validation step.

It comes after the proposal and negotiation.

It‚Äôs an internal step for:
‚Äì The CEO or VP of Sales to review the deal.
‚Äì The SDR or sales manager to self-analyze.
‚Äì An item to discuss during weekly or monthly deal reviews.

The key focus of validation?

Double-check the customer still fits your ICP.

It‚Äôs overlooked because:
‚Äì The SDR wants to hit quota.
‚Äì The sales manager wants to hit quota.
‚Äì Or simply, the revenue is too tempting to resist.

But if you‚Äôre serious about scaling to 8 or 9 figures, you must take this step.

You must reconsider going ahead if the ICP isn‚Äôt the right fit.

Here‚Äôs why‚Ä¶

I recently read a story from Jake Fuentes, co-founder of Cascade, about why he shut his startup down.

He admitted that ‚ÄúICP fray‚Äù was a key factor.

Cascade initially defined their ICP as ‚Äúnontechnical business analysts using Excel to crunch big data sets‚Äù.

The definition was too broad.

They ended up chasing customers with wildly different use cases:
‚Äì A scooter company managing location data.
‚Äì An HR team managing employee data.

They didn‚Äôt have a framework to accept or reject opportunities, so they tried to support them all.

Jake described this as ‚Äúa slow death of a thousand cuts.‚Äù

Supporting anyone and everyone pulled the company in a million directions, ultimately diluting their focus and stunting growth.

If you want to scale successfully, rejecting deals from prospects who don‚Äôt fit your ICP is the tough but necessary way forward.

Validate every deal.

Stick to your guns.

Keep closing.

posts.content:
We‚Äôre about to be inundated with AI crap.

AI is a powerful tool but absent intelligent design it will dump the average of everything into poorly defined apps, poorly written emails, and pages and pages of content that don‚Äôt say anything meaningful.

Non-technical Founders that are overly reliant on AI will rely on average code to produce average results.

The market will be flooded with bad products.

There will be good products as well.

But lots of and lots of crap.

The value of quality, judgement and taste will continue grow.

Over time, the market will sort itself out.

BUT:

- Community and peer conversation
- Rating and ranking systems
- Filters and curators

Will continue to command a premium.

There‚Äôs no accounting for taste.

And, as Karl Lagerfeld said, ‚ÄúIf you‚Äôre cheap, nothing helps.‚Äù

18 Quiet Habits of Top Salespeople:

1. They close deals without making noise.
‚Ü≥ Results matter, not showing off.

2. They let the client talk first and last.
‚Ü≥ Clients talk, you listen.

3. They sell the outcome, not the product.
‚Ü≥ Focus on results, not features.

4. They stay in the room when others walk away.
‚Ü≥ Don‚Äôt quit when it‚Äôs tough.

5. They control emotions‚Äîno highs, no lows.
‚Ü≥ Stay calm no matter what.

6. They let silence do the heavy lifting.
‚Ü≥ Silence pushes decisions.

7. They never beg for the deal.
‚Ü≥ Confidence closes, begging kills.

8. They earn respect, not attention.
‚Ü≥ Respect is stronger than noise.

9. They keep their poker face, no matter what‚Äôs said.
‚Ü≥ Stay cool, even in tough talks.

10. They handle objections before they‚Äôre spoken.
‚Ü≥ Solve problems before they come up.

11. They kill jargon and speak human.
‚Ü≥ Talk simple, stay real.

12. They don‚Äôt just follow up‚Äîthey stay top of mind.
‚Ü≥ Follow-ups keep clients thinking of you.

13. They never overpromise.
‚Ü≥ Say less, deliver more.

14. They work the deal, not the room.
‚Ü≥ Focus only where it matters.

15. They show up ready, not hopeful.
‚Ü≥ Be prepared or go home.

16. They make clients feel they discovered the solution.
‚Ü≥ Let clients own the win.

17. They know when to put their ego aside.
‚Ü≥ Ego blocks success.

18. They focus on the client, not their own agenda.
‚Ü≥ The client‚Äôs goals come first.

Selling isn‚Äôt about being the loudest.

The best salespeople focus on mastery, trust, and quiet persistence.

Which habit stands out to you?

Let me know in the comments below!

Corporate Training on Mental Health Awareness at Work! 

On January 11, I had the pleasure of leading a mental health and well-being session for the incredible team at. The event, held at the elegant, was organized by WBS and turned out to be a memorable and impactful experience.

The session began with an in-depth discussion on the importance of mental health in the workplace, focusing on recognizing signs of stress, burnout, and anxiety. We explored strategies for managing these challenges effectively, including:
 Building emotional resilience
 Techniques for stress management
 The role of empathy and communication in fostering a healthy work environment

To provide personalized insights, participants completed the DAS-21 assessment, a scientifically-backed tool that helps measure depression, anxiety, and stress levels.

We didn‚Äôt stop there‚Äîlearning was combined with fun and interactive activities that brought the team together, fostered positive energy, and reinforced the importance of self-care and team support.

The enthusiasm, engagement, and genuine openness from the Revesolv team were truly inspiring. It‚Äôs always heartening to see organizations taking proactive steps toward creating healthier and more inclusive workplaces.

Looking forward to more collaborations like this, spreading the message that mental health is just as important as physical health!
